<h2 id="pets">Pets and Farm Animals</h2><p><strong>猫 (māo)</strong> cat, <strong>狗 (gǒu)</strong> dog, <strong>兔子 (tùzi)</strong> rabbit, <strong>鱼 (yú)</strong> fish, <strong>鸟 (niǎo)</strong> bird, <strong>马 (mǎ)</strong> horse, <strong>牛 (niú)</strong> cow, <strong>猪 (zhū)</strong> pig, <strong>羊 (yáng)</strong> sheep, <strong>鸡 (jī)</strong> chicken.</p>
    <h2 id="wild">Wild Animals</h2><p><strong>老虎 (lǎohǔ)</strong> tiger, <strong>熊猫 (xióngmāo)</strong> panda (literally "bear cat"), <strong>龙 (lóng)</strong> dragon, <strong>蛇 (shé)</strong> snake, <strong>猴子 (hóuzi)</strong> monkey, <strong>大象 (dàxiàng)</strong> elephant, <strong>狮子 (shīzi)</strong> lion.</p>
    <h2 id="cultural">Animals in Culture</h2><p>Animals carry rich symbolism in Chinese culture. The <strong>dragon (龙)</strong> represents power and good fortune. The <strong>phoenix (凤凰, fènghuáng)</strong> symbolizes grace and virtue. <strong>Fish (鱼)</strong> represents abundance because it sounds like 余 (surplus). Practice writing animal characters with our <a href="/chinese/tools/practice-sheet/">Practice Sheet Generator</a>.</p>
